00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:54.290
So if you are interested,
they're available in the back.

00:01:54.290 --> 00:01:56.480
And we will also have time
for questions at the end.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:59.372
So friendly reminder up front,
and I'll repeat it again,

00:01:59.372 --> 00:02:01.580
when you do have a question,
don't just shout it out.

00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:05.180
Line up behind the mics so that
we can get it on the recording.

00:02:05.180 --> 00:02:07.550
ROB SMITH: And I'll be around
to sign any copies that

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:08.974
are purchased today as well.

00:02:08.974 --> 00:02:10.280
JIMMY PEARSON: Cool.

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:13.960
So yesterday was
international coming out day.

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.070
And there is a really
interesting excerpt

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:18.182
in your book from when
you came out to your mom.

00:02:18.182 --> 00:02:20.390
And I thought given that
international coming out day

00:02:20.390 --> 00:02:22.640
was yesterday, that might
be an appropriate place

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:24.320
to start if you want, if
you don't mind reading it.

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:25.945
ROB SMITH: I don't
mind reading at all,

00:02:25.945 --> 00:02:28.360
that's while we're here.

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:30.350
Yeah, yesterday
was coming out day.

00:02:30.350 --> 00:02:32.600
And did a lot of
tweeting, usually

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:35.540
do talks on coming out day.

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:38.030
To me, coming out
day is about being

00:02:38.030 --> 00:02:41.532
represented in all of your
identities everywhere you are.

00:02:41.532 --> 00:02:43.740
I don't have to come out as
a black man all the time.

00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:46.115
This is the first thing that
people see when they see me.

00:02:46.115 --> 00:02:50.630
But I am put in the position
to come out as a gay man,

00:02:50.630 --> 00:02:54.200
over, and over, and over
again, and you pick and choose

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:56.720
the different ways that
you want to come out.

00:02:56.720 --> 00:02:58.790
Now this excerpt that
I'm going to read right

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:02.720
now is me coming out over
the phone to my mother

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:05.450
when I was very young,
and when I was just

00:03:05.450 --> 00:03:06.980
starting out in the military.

00:03:06.980 --> 00:03:08.990
It did not go
well, and I'll just

00:03:08.990 --> 00:03:10.560
read this little bit for you.

00:03:13.957 --> 00:03:15.540
I opened the door
to the barracks room

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:19.140
slowly and discreetly and picked
up the phone to dial my mother.

00:03:19.140 --> 00:03:20.700
I wasn't sure why
I felt the need

00:03:20.700 --> 00:03:23.400
to do to provide a
teaser to a conversation

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:25.740
that we wouldn't be
having for two months,

00:03:25.740 --> 00:03:28.930
but a strong sense of
relief had come over me

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:33.450
ever since I admitted it to
myself, I'm gay, I like guys.

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:36.600
I heard her warm, yet gravelly
voice, on the other end.

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:38.190
She'd obviously been smoking.

00:03:38.190 --> 00:03:40.170
"Hello," she said.

00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:41.760
"Hey mom, it's me,
how you doing?"

00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:43.125
"Fine, and you?"

00:03:43.125 --> 00:03:44.790
"I'm OK, what are you up to?"

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:47.230
"Just driving,
Robert, what's up?"

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:48.960
"Uh, nothing."

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:50.640
I felt my throat
begin to close up.

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:52.890
I suddenly became
tense and nervous,

00:03:52.890 --> 00:03:55.912
and I was struggling to
find the words to say.

00:03:55.912 --> 00:03:57.370
"So why are you
calling me, Robert?

00:03:57.370 --> 00:03:59.100
I'm on the road driving."

00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:01.519
Husband number three
lived in North Carolina.

00:04:01.519 --> 00:04:03.060
He worked for a
truck driving company

00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:05.130
that delivered loads
of various products

00:04:05.130 --> 00:04:06.660
all across the country.

00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:09.030
She'd moved down my
senior year of high school

00:04:09.030 --> 00:04:11.400
and embarked on a career
in driving, leaving

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:12.990
me to live with
paternal grandparents

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:14.910
for the remainder of my time.

00:04:14.910 --> 00:04:17.351
"Um, OK, you know I'm coming
back home for Christmas,

00:04:17.351 --> 00:04:17.850
right?"

00:04:17.850 --> 00:04:20.024
"Yes, Robert, I know."

00:04:20.024 --> 00:04:23.310
"Well, there's something I
wanted to talk to you about."

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:26.801
There was a long uncomfortable
stream of absolute silence.

00:04:26.801 --> 00:04:28.800
I could hear the wind
whipping in the background

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:31.320
from the cracked window
of her 18 wheeler.

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:34.080
I wondered what city she was
driving to this time, what

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:36.390
the scenery was like
wherever she was,

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:39.430
anything to fill the silence.

00:04:39.430 --> 00:04:43.119
After what seemed like forever,
she continued, "What is it?

00:04:43.119 --> 00:04:44.160
You're not gay, are you?"

00:04:46.770 --> 00:04:49.710
The words hit me like a
well-timed punch to the gut.

00:04:49.710 --> 00:04:51.400
My knees buckled a little bit.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.170
And I stumbled onto the
corner of my bed, shocked.

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:56.100
"Well, what if I was?"

00:04:56.100 --> 00:04:58.425
I said, in a quiet
little boy voice.

00:04:58.425 --> 00:05:00.990
"Robert, you know that's not
allowed in the army," she said.

00:05:00.990 --> 00:05:04.020
"You also know that's
not God's plan."

00:05:04.020 --> 00:05:07.290
Her voice was cold and
harsh, unforgiving.

00:05:07.290 --> 00:05:09.566
Whatever the words to
respond to this were,

00:05:09.566 --> 00:05:10.440
I couldn't find them.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:11.850
"Do you hear me?"

00:05:11.850 --> 00:05:13.370
She said.

00:05:13.370 --> 00:05:16.390
I felt like I was adrift, like
I was floating above myself

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:17.870
watching this happen.

00:05:17.870 --> 00:05:19.610
It wasn't supposed
to happen like this.

00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:21.770
I was supposed to
call and give her

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:24.307
a primer that I wanted to
talk to her about something,

00:05:24.307 --> 00:05:26.390
so that maybe it wouldn't
be such a big shock when

00:05:26.390 --> 00:05:28.169
I told her during the holiday.

00:05:28.169 --> 00:05:29.960
When I did tell her
after Christmas dinner,

00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:32.660
she would hug me and tell
me that she loved me,

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:35.540
and that I was her
son no matter what.

00:05:35.540 --> 00:05:37.430
I would hug her
back as tears of joy

00:05:37.430 --> 00:05:40.610
streamed down my cheeks,
while flurries of perfectly

00:05:40.610 --> 00:05:43.160
soft white snow fell outside.

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:46.070
That was how it was supposed
to happen, but it wasn't.

00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:49.010
It was happening right now,
and I wasn't exactly feeling

00:05:49.010 --> 00:05:50.720
the love.

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:55.342
"Yes, I hear you," I said,
in a low-defeated croak.

00:05:55.342 --> 00:05:58.062
"And you better not tell anybody
else either, you hear me boy?

00:05:58.062 --> 00:05:59.770
Those people there
are not to be trusted,

00:05:59.770 --> 00:06:01.070
and you can't be
getting kicked out.

00:06:01.070 --> 00:06:03.528
How are you going to pay for
college if you get kicked out?

00:06:03.528 --> 00:06:04.940
Where you going to live?"

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:06.025
"I don't know, mom."

00:06:06.025 --> 00:06:08.086
"I know you don't.

00:06:08.086 --> 00:06:09.460
Is that what you
called me about?

00:06:09.460 --> 00:06:10.990
I got to get back to driving.

00:06:10.990 --> 00:06:12.640
Call me next week."

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:15.730
She hung up, and I sat on the
edge of the bed, motionless.

00:06:15.730 --> 00:06:19.090
Soon after, I
realized I was crying.

00:06:19.090 --> 00:06:21.610
Out in the distance I could
hear the faint chant of soldiers

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:24.000
calling cadence while they ran.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.010
Their voices comforted me.

00:06:26.010 --> 00:06:29.270
When I heard them, it was
almost as if I wasn't so alone.

00:06:29.270 --> 00:06:31.815
And it was only when they
stopped that I knew I was.

00:06:34.926 --> 00:06:35.878
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:38.420 --> 00:06:40.170
JIMMY PEARSON: Thank
you for reading that.

00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:41.820
I think, it's actually
kind of funny,

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:45.859
because I feel my own heart
rate rising as I sit here,

00:06:45.859 --> 00:06:48.150
hearing you read it, because
I think a lot of-- there's

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:50.880
a lot of similarities between
a lot of coming out experience.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:52.902
And clearly, I
could see that you

00:06:52.902 --> 00:06:55.235
were transported back there
a little bit as you read it.

00:06:55.235 --> 00:06:58.572
And I appreciate you
sharing that with us.

00:06:58.572 --> 00:07:00.030
One thing I wanted
to ask you about

00:07:00.030 --> 00:07:01.830
is the very end of
that passage where

00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:04.260
you talk about hearing
the soldier's calling

00:07:04.260 --> 00:07:07.579
cadence in the background and
feeling comforted, but then

00:07:07.579 --> 00:07:08.620
feeling very, very alone.

00:07:08.620 --> 00:07:12.227
And I wanted to ask you, I think
that that points to something

00:07:12.227 --> 00:07:14.310
that kind of runs throughout
the book, of the Army

00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:17.400
being a source of community
and a source of comfort

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:19.392
in a lot of
circumstances, but also,

00:07:19.392 --> 00:07:20.850
in some ways,
because of Don't Ask,

00:07:20.850 --> 00:07:26.190
Don't Tell, exacerbating your
loneliness at the same time.

00:07:26.190 --> 00:07:27.450
Was it both of those things?

00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:30.360
Was it really more one of
those things than the other?

00:07:30.360 --> 00:07:32.650
What was that
juxtaposition like for you?

00:07:32.650 --> 00:07:35.024
ROB SMITH: You know, I think
it was both of those things.

00:07:35.024 --> 00:07:37.050
I think that when I
talk about the military,

00:07:37.050 --> 00:07:39.360
and when you read the
book, you'll find out,

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:42.840
a lot of people think that
just writing this book,

00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:45.000
that I'm here to
bash the military

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.610
or bash being a vet or
anything, because they actually

00:07:47.610 --> 00:07:49.890
had that discriminatory
policy for so long.

00:07:49.890 --> 00:07:51.250
And that's not what I do.

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:52.870
I think things are more--

00:07:52.870 --> 00:07:54.390
there are more shades of gray.

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:56.250
It's not a total
black and white thing.

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:57.660
When I was in the
military, I did

00:07:57.660 --> 00:08:01.050
feel completely isolated
from other people, purely

00:08:01.050 --> 00:08:02.700
because of my
sexual orientation,

00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:04.770
because I knew what it
was, and because I also

00:08:04.770 --> 00:08:08.187
knew that I could get kicked out
of the military at any point.

00:08:08.187 --> 00:08:10.020
And when I talk about
Don't Ask, Don't Tell,

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:13.410
and when I talk about
serving under that,

00:08:13.410 --> 00:08:15.570
I think it's really
important for people

00:08:15.570 --> 00:08:19.134
to realize that what happens
when you get kicked out under

00:08:19.134 --> 00:08:20.550
Don't Ask, Don't
Tell, is that you

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:22.050
get a dishonorable discharge.

00:08:22.050 --> 00:08:24.240
That means college
benefits gone,

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:25.740
health care benefits gone.

00:08:25.740 --> 00:08:29.730
All of these things that have
made my life so much better

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:32.970
as a veteran, who did get
an honorable discharge,

00:08:32.970 --> 00:08:34.600
would get taken away.

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:36.831
And I think that
that really connects

00:08:36.831 --> 00:08:38.789
to a lot of the battles
that we're having right

00:08:38.789 --> 00:08:45.000
now as an LGBTQ community about
equal workplace protections.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.570
Conversations that we're
having with trans people being

00:08:48.570 --> 00:08:50.730
able to be open and out
about their identities

00:08:50.730 --> 00:08:52.120
at work right now.

00:08:52.120 --> 00:08:55.590
So I felt very alone, very
isolated because of this.

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:59.490
But at the same time, I had
a lot of good relationships

00:08:59.490 --> 00:09:01.750
with people that I served with.

00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:03.120
I had a lot of good times.

00:09:03.120 --> 00:09:04.440
I felt a lot of camaraderie.

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:05.350
I felt a brotherhood.

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:07.740
And I only say brotherhood,
because the infantry was all

00:09:07.740 --> 00:09:08.790
male.

00:09:08.790 --> 00:09:11.760
So that was a combat
position that wasn't

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:13.600
open to women at the time.

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:15.730
So I really did feel all that.

00:09:15.730 --> 00:09:18.330
But at the same time,
having to serve under

00:09:18.330 --> 00:09:21.370
Don't Ask, Don't Tell, made
it that much more difficult.

00:09:21.370 --> 00:09:23.690
I felt like I couldn't
be my entire self.

00:09:23.690 --> 00:09:25.440
We have these conversations
about bringing

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:29.250
our entire selves to the
workplace when we are LGBTQ,

00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:32.220
or we are Latino,
or African-American,

00:09:32.220 --> 00:09:34.630
or any of these other
different identities.

00:09:34.630 --> 00:09:37.080
And I felt like I couldn't
bring my entire identity

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:39.660
to that workplace.

00:09:39.660 --> 00:09:43.020
JIMMY PEARSON: Do you think
that that inhibited your ability

00:09:43.020 --> 00:09:44.910
as a soldier in any way?

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:49.230
ROB SMITH: Absolutely, because
serving in the military

00:09:49.230 --> 00:09:52.780
depends on you bringing
100% of yourself to the job.

00:09:52.780 --> 00:09:54.300
I was a good soldier.

00:09:54.300 --> 00:09:55.920
I was an OK soldier.

00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:58.110
I felt, when looking
back at it, I

00:09:58.110 --> 00:09:59.790
feel like if I was
able to be out,

00:09:59.790 --> 00:10:01.440
I could have been
a great soldier,

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:03.120
I could have been
an amazing soldier.

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:07.560
Because I wouldn't have had to
have that barrier that's there,

00:10:07.560 --> 00:10:11.130
that had to be there to keep
me from everywhere else.

00:10:11.130 --> 00:10:13.800
I feel like right now, in
the position that I'm in,

00:10:13.800 --> 00:10:15.840
whether it's reporting
at Yahoo Finance,

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:18.240
whether it's doing
talks, and things

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:22.604
like that, I'm able to bring
my entire self to work.

00:10:22.604 --> 00:10:25.020
And even though that may not
be the most comfortable thing

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:27.990
at all times for other people,
it's more comfortable for me,

00:10:27.990 --> 00:10:30.092
because I feel like I don't
have anything to hide.

00:10:30.092 --> 00:10:31.800
I don't have to hide
the fact that I just

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:33.030
got married a month ago.

00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:35.840
I don't have to watch my--

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:37.550
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:37.550 --> 00:10:38.270
Thanks.

00:10:38.270 --> 00:10:38.610
JIMMY PEARSON: Congratulations.

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:39.870
ROB SMITH: Thank you.

00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:42.000
You guys will applaud if
you guys see his cape.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.130
Follow me on Instagram.

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:47.340
