Case in point, we
look at the images

00:21:53.930 --> 00:21:56.660
that we have of LGBTQ
people in the media.

00:21:56.660 --> 00:22:00.290
And still to this day, they
tend to be primarily images

00:22:00.290 --> 00:22:02.430
of white gay men.

00:22:02.430 --> 00:22:04.560
And this is something
that's starting to change.

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:06.350
And I'm glad that
this is changing.

00:22:06.350 --> 00:22:09.500
But even to this day, I
do an Instagram account

00:22:09.500 --> 00:22:11.630
with my husband at
Robert and Misha.

00:22:11.630 --> 00:22:13.730
And sometimes we
get liked, and we

00:22:13.730 --> 00:22:16.370
get commented by a lot
of these other blogs,

00:22:16.370 --> 00:22:19.250
that are like cutest gay
couples, or gay couples,

00:22:19.250 --> 00:22:20.180
or whatever.

00:22:20.180 --> 00:22:23.450
So I look at these
Instagram feeds,

00:22:23.450 --> 00:22:25.340
and they are
completely dominated

00:22:25.340 --> 00:22:28.250
by white gay male couples.

00:22:28.250 --> 00:22:30.050
And this Instagram
we're talking about.

00:22:30.050 --> 00:22:33.110
Like this is 2017 going on 2018.

00:22:33.110 --> 00:22:36.950
And there are a lot of different
things in the community that

00:22:36.950 --> 00:22:40.370
can divide us, from race,
to socioeconomic status,

00:22:40.370 --> 00:22:41.670
to all those different things.

00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:45.320
And I've definitely experienced
my fair share of racism

00:22:45.320 --> 00:22:47.120
in the LGBTQ community.

00:22:47.120 --> 00:22:49.460
I've experienced my
fair share of classism.

00:22:49.460 --> 00:22:51.800
These are things that
are definitely happening

00:22:51.800 --> 00:22:53.420
and definitely still going on.

00:22:53.420 --> 00:22:57.980
But the good thing about now,
where we're sitting right here

00:22:57.980 --> 00:22:59.960
and talking about
this in 2017, is

00:22:59.960 --> 00:23:02.870
I think that we are now starting
to talk about these things

00:23:02.870 --> 00:23:03.800
more.

00:23:03.800 --> 00:23:07.400
And when you speak about them
more, and you speak to them,

00:23:07.400 --> 00:23:11.480
I think that it allows
us, and it gives us

00:23:11.480 --> 00:23:14.610
the tools to try to change
some of these things.

00:23:14.610 --> 00:23:19.060
So if I say on Twitter, or
I write an article about why

00:23:19.060 --> 00:23:21.980
are so many heads of
LGBTQ organizations

00:23:21.980 --> 00:23:24.650
white people will
talk about that.

00:23:24.650 --> 00:23:26.330
And people say why is this.

00:23:26.330 --> 00:23:31.070
And when transgender women
and men speak up and say,

00:23:31.070 --> 00:23:34.224
we need to be represented, and
why are all these trans women

00:23:34.224 --> 00:23:36.140
white and then we have
people like Laverne Cox

00:23:36.140 --> 00:23:38.900
and Janet Mock come out,
and then kind of like change

00:23:38.900 --> 00:23:43.130
that conversation around what
the face of transgender is.

00:23:43.130 --> 00:23:45.680
And I think that for me,
in writing this book,

00:23:45.680 --> 00:23:48.530
and making the very
specific choice

00:23:48.530 --> 00:23:53.060
to put my image on the
cover, is saying that this is

00:23:53.060 --> 00:23:54.860
a book about a black gay man.

00:23:54.860 --> 00:23:58.190
And I'm going to put
my face on the cover.

00:23:58.190 --> 00:23:59.900
Because back in
the day, when I was

00:23:59.900 --> 00:24:01.733
talking to publishers
and things about that,

00:24:01.733 --> 00:24:04.490
one thing about the
publishing industry

00:24:04.490 --> 00:24:10.190
is that you will be told
in not uncertain terms

00:24:10.190 --> 00:24:12.860
that sometimes putting a
black face on the cover

00:24:12.860 --> 00:24:14.880
is not going to sell.

00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:15.824
JIMMY PEARSON: Really?

00:24:15.824 --> 00:24:16.990
ROB SMITH: Yeah, absolutely.

00:24:16.990 --> 00:24:20.950
And even doing things
that are LGBT oriented,

00:24:20.950 --> 00:24:23.270
putting a black face on the
cover is not going to sell.

00:24:23.270 --> 00:24:25.780
So it was very important
for me to represent myself

00:24:25.780 --> 00:24:28.480
and other black
gay men, I think,

00:24:28.480 --> 00:24:30.034
by putting myself on the cover.

00:24:30.034 --> 00:24:31.450
JIMMY PEARSON: We
should see if we

00:24:31.450 --> 00:24:33.880
can prove them wrong by
buying a lot of gay books

00:24:33.880 --> 00:24:35.270
with a black person
on the cover.

00:24:35.270 --> 00:24:36.250
ROB SMITH: Absolutely.

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:37.380
But there should be more.

00:24:37.380 --> 00:24:40.870
And a point to that is
that, still to this day,

00:24:40.870 --> 00:24:45.610
we are going on, what, 15
years after the war in Iraq.

00:24:45.610 --> 00:24:49.900
This is still one of, I
believe less than five books

00:24:49.900 --> 00:24:52.960
that have been written by
African-American soldiers

00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:55.060
of any sexual
orientation or gender

00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:58.180
identity about their
experiences in Iraq.

00:24:58.180 --> 00:25:01.330
So in writing this book,
and in doing this--

00:25:01.330 --> 00:25:05.530
and I like to bill it as
"Moonlight" meets American--

00:25:05.530 --> 00:25:07.540
"Moonlight" meets
"American Sniper."

00:25:07.540 --> 00:25:13.390
So the question is why, when
we look at these books that

00:25:13.390 --> 00:25:15.820
are about the military,
when we watch these movies,

00:25:15.820 --> 00:25:18.430
when we watch these
miniseries, why are they always

00:25:18.430 --> 00:25:22.570
about straight white
men, when the military is

00:25:22.570 --> 00:25:24.610
one of the most
diverse organizations

00:25:24.610 --> 00:25:27.950
you'll ever work in your life,
you know, I've ever worked in.

00:25:27.950 --> 00:25:30.072
It's still the only place
in my entire career,

00:25:30.072 --> 00:25:32.530
and I've done a lot of things,
where I've had a black boss.

00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:35.620
It's still the only place
I've ever had a black boss.

00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:41.480
So I really wanted to make
sure that that was represented.

00:25:41.480 --> 00:25:42.980
JIMMY PEARSON: It's
interesting when

00:25:42.980 --> 00:25:45.750
you talk about how you lived
these in the early 2000s,

00:25:45.750 --> 00:25:47.815
and now it's 2017, and
things have changed,

00:25:47.815 --> 00:25:48.940
but there's still the same.

00:25:48.940 --> 00:25:49.820
ROB SMITH: Yeah.

00:25:49.820 --> 00:25:51.290
JIMMY PEARSON: I'm a little
embarrassed to admit this,

00:25:51.290 --> 00:25:52.430
one of the first things
that came to my mind

00:25:52.430 --> 00:25:53.330
was "Will and Grace."

00:25:53.330 --> 00:25:54.144
ROB SMITH: Yeah.

00:25:54.144 --> 00:25:55.810
JIMMY PEARSON: It was
popular back then,

00:25:55.810 --> 00:25:59.030
and it's now back, God help us.

00:25:59.030 --> 00:26:01.460
And it's always been
kind of controversial,

00:26:01.460 --> 00:26:05.990
specifically because it paints
a very specific white, affluent,

00:26:05.990 --> 00:26:07.850
urban picture of what
gay life is like.

00:26:07.850 --> 00:26:11.750
ROB SMITH: It does, and I think
the reason why is because--

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:16.022
and this speaks to having people
of color that are actually

00:26:16.022 --> 00:26:18.230
writing, and having people
of color that are actually

00:26:18.230 --> 00:26:18.980
creating.

00:26:18.980 --> 00:26:22.222
Because the first thing,
when-- the first bit of advice

00:26:22.222 --> 00:26:23.930
that people give you
as a writer, is they

00:26:23.930 --> 00:26:25.202
say write what you know.

00:26:25.202 --> 00:26:26.660
And if we have a
lot of people that

00:26:26.660 --> 00:26:29.480
are in positions of power
that are even putting out

00:26:29.480 --> 00:26:31.516
gay or LGBTQ content,
that are white guys,

00:26:31.516 --> 00:26:33.890
the first thing they're going
to write is what they know.

00:26:33.890 --> 00:26:36.260
What they know is upper
middle class, white gay guys,

00:26:36.260 --> 00:26:37.940
living in large cities.

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:40.580
And that's great, because God
knows, there's a lot of them.

00:26:40.580 --> 00:26:43.040
But there's also a lot of
different people having

00:26:43.040 --> 00:26:44.970
a lot of different experiences.

00:26:44.970 --> 00:26:47.630
And the most exciting
thing now is--

00:26:47.630 --> 00:26:52.556
I'm having a meeting with some
agents in a couple of weeks,

00:26:52.556 --> 00:26:53.930
because I'm really
trying to push

00:26:53.930 --> 00:26:56.450
like getting this adapter
for the big screen,

00:26:56.450 --> 00:26:58.310
or Netflix, or
something like that.

00:26:58.310 --> 00:27:00.860
I think that the most
exciting thing right now

00:27:00.860 --> 00:27:03.710
is that there's so many
platforms out there.

00:27:03.710 --> 00:27:05.650
So not only do we have
the Legacy Networks,

00:27:05.650 --> 00:27:08.150
but we have the Hulu's and the
Netflix's and the Facebook's,

00:27:08.150 --> 00:27:09.690
and all that stuff.

00:27:09.690 --> 00:27:12.680
And there's so much
more opportunity

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:15.320
to get different
stories that represent

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:17.482
marginalized
communities out there.

00:27:17.482 --> 00:27:19.190
And if you have a
movie like "Moonlight,"

00:27:19.190 --> 00:27:23.030
that just won an Academy
Award for Best Picture, that

00:27:23.030 --> 00:27:26.840
means that somewhere out
there, somewhere, there

00:27:26.840 --> 00:27:30.350
are people that are open and
receptive to these stories.

00:27:30.350 --> 00:27:33.052
And I think that now
is the time for that.

00:27:33.052 --> 00:27:35.510
Even though the new "Will and
Grace" is still pretty funny.

00:27:35.510 --> 00:27:36.385
JIMMY PEARSON: Is it?

00:27:36.385 --> 00:27:37.280
ROB SMITH: It's OK.

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:38.120
JIMMY PEARSON: I wasn't
a fan of the original.

00:27:38.120 --> 00:27:39.620
I gave myself away earlier.

00:27:39.620 --> 00:27:41.510
I wasn't really a
fan of the original.

00:27:41.510 --> 00:27:42.650
Well, that's cool.

00:27:42.650 --> 00:27:43.595
ROB SMITH: Yeah.

00:27:43.595 --> 00:27:45.220
JIMMY PEARSON: And
one other question I

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:46.636
have about this
idea of acceptance

00:27:46.636 --> 00:27:50.720
in the LGBT community is,
what about as a veteran

00:27:50.720 --> 00:27:54.999
specifically, do you feel that
you are viewed differently,

00:27:54.999 --> 00:27:57.290
for better or worse, as a
veteran in the gay community?

00:27:57.290 --> 00:27:58.540
Or does it not come up at all?

00:27:58.540 --> 00:28:00.665
ROB SMITH: It doesn't come
up in the gay community.

00:28:00.665 --> 00:28:03.190
I can talk to being a veteran
in the overall community.

00:28:03.190 --> 00:28:03.350
JIMMY PEARSON: Sure.

00:28:03.350 --> 00:28:04.820
ROB SMITH: And what I'll
say about being a veteran,

00:28:04.820 --> 00:28:06.230
just in the
community in general,

00:28:06.230 --> 00:28:08.576
is that people don't
understand, people

00:28:08.576 --> 00:28:09.950
don't understand
being a veteran.

00:28:09.950 --> 00:28:11.570
People don't respect
being a veteran.

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:16.280
People think military
service is strange and odd.

00:28:16.280 --> 00:28:18.110
These are things
that I've dealt with

00:28:18.110 --> 00:28:21.380
and a lot of different workplace
situations I've been in.

00:28:21.380 --> 00:28:26.270
When you have an all-volunteer
military that adds up to,

00:28:26.270 --> 00:28:30.500
I think maybe 1% to 3%
of America's population,

00:28:30.500 --> 00:28:33.050
and this is specifically
talking about America,

00:28:33.050 --> 00:28:37.010
then chances are that the
vast majority of people

00:28:37.010 --> 00:28:39.590
don't know anybody
who served, have never

00:28:39.590 --> 00:28:42.860
met anybody who served, don't
have anybody in their family

00:28:42.860 --> 00:28:43.700
who served.

00:28:43.700 --> 00:28:45.150
So they have no idea.

00:28:45.150 --> 00:28:50.270
And so the idea is
that these are just--

00:28:50.270 --> 00:28:53.060
poor people are just
cannon fodder for America.

00:28:53.060 --> 00:28:57.050
And that's some of the
feedback that I've gotten.

00:28:57.050 --> 00:29:00.410
And this is stuff that
comes from wealthy liberals

00:29:00.410 --> 00:29:01.580
on the coasts.

00:29:01.580 --> 00:29:05.210
And these are some of the ideas
that people carry with them,

00:29:05.210 --> 00:29:07.010
before they find out
that I'm a veteran.

00:29:07.010 --> 00:29:10.940
And then I make things
very awkward for them

00:29:10.940 --> 00:29:12.390
when they bring this stuff up.

00:29:12.390 --> 00:29:13.765
And then people
talk about things

00:29:13.765 --> 00:29:16.910
like the military industrial
complex and all that.

00:29:16.910 --> 00:29:19.279
And those are valid arguments.

00:29:19.279 --> 00:29:20.820
Those are valid
things to talk about.

00:29:20.820 --> 00:29:24.890
And even in the
LGBTQ community, I

00:29:24.890 --> 00:29:27.470
think that speaking
about veterans issues

00:29:27.470 --> 00:29:30.860
and speaking positively
of the military

00:29:30.860 --> 00:29:35.390
is seen as somehow conservative
or right leaning, which

00:29:35.390 --> 00:29:36.860
I've never understood.

00:29:36.860 --> 00:29:41.120
But I've gotten that feedback
within our community as well.

00:29:41.120 --> 00:29:44.300
And I've never quite understood
that, because for me,

00:29:44.300 --> 00:29:50.000
the military was the way to
expand my life and my borders

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:53.870
beyond the small town
that I was raised in Ohio,

00:29:53.870 --> 00:29:57.050
the small city of Akron, Ohio.

00:29:57.050 --> 00:30:00.060
So I think that we have
a lot of work to do,

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:04.010
both as an LGBTQ community,
and as a mainstream American

00:30:04.010 --> 00:30:05.482
community in general.

00:30:05.482 --> 00:30:07.190
We have a lot of work
to do when it comes

00:30:07.190 --> 00:30:08.810
to understanding veterans.

00:30:08.810 --> 00:30:11.740
And also, people that
are in hiring positions

00:30:11.740 --> 00:30:16.460
in organizations, instead of
the first thing that you think

00:30:16.460 --> 00:30:19.670
about when you talk to
a veteran is about PTSD,

00:30:19.670 --> 00:30:22.430
or how horrible war must
be, or anything like that,

00:30:22.430 --> 00:30:25.370
think about what
this person may be

00:30:25.370 --> 00:30:28.250
able to bring to this
organization, what

00:30:28.250 --> 00:30:31.520
are the qualities that
the military instills

00:30:31.520 --> 00:30:34.160
in people that could help
in your organization.

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:37.530
I will tell you that
for me personally,

00:30:37.530 --> 00:30:40.010
it just gave me a higher
level of discipline

00:30:40.010 --> 00:30:43.130
than a lot of people
that I work with in a lot

00:30:43.130 --> 00:30:45.500
of different situations.

00:30:45.500 --> 00:30:47.000
JIMMY PEARSON: It's
interesting, you

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:48.440
brought up a really
good point that I

00:30:48.440 --> 00:30:50.190
think is a little under
appreciated, which

00:30:50.190 --> 00:30:53.840
is not only is the
all-volunteer force so small,

00:30:53.840 --> 00:30:55.790
just numbers, say, a
few people are going

00:30:55.790 --> 00:30:57.590
to have interactions with it.

00:30:57.590 --> 00:31:03.530
But it's also disproportionately
southern, lower

00:31:03.530 --> 00:31:04.781
on the economic ladder.

00:31:04.781 --> 00:31:06.530
ROB SMITH: Lower middle
class, absolutely.

00:31:06.530 --> 00:31:10.140
JIMMY PEARSON: Yeah,
and so, a lot of these--

00:31:10.140 --> 00:31:12.380
I think you used the term
wealthy coastal liberal

00:31:12.380 --> 00:31:13.850
or something like that--

00:31:13.850 --> 00:31:16.610
are especially removed
from it, in a way.

00:31:16.610 --> 00:31:18.410
ROB SMITH: Very much
removed from it.

00:31:18.410 --> 00:31:20.420
JIMMY PEARSON: So
in the interest

00:31:20.420 --> 00:31:23.180
of spreading a little
bit more about what

00:31:23.180 --> 00:31:25.380
the experience of being
in Iraq is actually like--

00:31:25.380 --> 00:31:26.230
ROB SMITH: Yes.

00:31:26.230 --> 00:31:26.990
JIMMY PEARSON:
That's a good a segue

00:31:26.990 --> 00:31:29.720
as any into the last passage
that you're going to read.

00:31:29.720 --> 00:31:30.440
ROB SMITH: It is.

00:31:30.440 --> 00:31:32.180
And I will keep this
brief, because I

00:31:32.180 --> 00:31:35.760
know we wanted to open
it up for questions.

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:39.410
So this is-- here we go.

00:31:39.410 --> 00:31:41.630
And this is very short.

00:31:41.630 --> 00:31:46.160
So this is basically, I served
for slightly under a year right

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:48.140
after the initial invasion.

00:31:48.140 --> 00:31:52.940
My-- actually my entire
company convoyed into Iraq.

00:31:52.940 --> 00:31:55.880
So we drove from
Kuwait into Iraq.

00:31:55.880 --> 00:32:02.190
And we kind of made little
pit stops along the way.

00:32:02.190 --> 00:32:03.940
And this is describing that.

00:32:08.530 --> 00:32:11.620
When we crossed the border into
Iraq just a few hours later,

00:32:11.620 --> 00:32:14.560
I noticed an immediate
difference in the scenery.

00:32:14.560 --> 00:32:17.230
The streets of Iraq had a
look of war-strewn desperation

00:32:17.230 --> 00:32:19.120
to them that was
hard to stomach.

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:21.100
Everywhere I looked
I saw Arabic language

00:32:21.100 --> 00:32:22.660
that I couldn't understand.

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:25.150
The roadsides were littered
with abandoned fighter vehicles

00:32:25.150 --> 00:32:28.180
that the Saddam loyalists had
used in their futile attempts

00:32:28.180 --> 00:32:31.950
to defend themselves against
the American invaders.

00:32:31.950 --> 00:32:34.950
Small, brown Iraqi children
would come out of nowhere

00:32:34.950 --> 00:32:37.470
sometimes, running and
waving with the tanks.

00:32:37.470 --> 00:32:39.810
We were moving slow
enough in the 15 to 20

00:32:39.810 --> 00:32:42.990
vehicle convoy for them to
keep up with to a point.

00:32:42.990 --> 00:32:45.990
They wore tattered pants and
t-shirts with logos and brands

00:32:45.990 --> 00:32:48.660
from them that were
distinctly from the '80s.

00:32:48.660 --> 00:32:50.760
Their high voices were
filled with joy and hope

00:32:50.760 --> 00:32:54.810
as they chanted, "America, USA,"
with bright smiles and hands

00:32:54.810 --> 00:32:57.180
extended in the
thumbs up position.

00:32:57.180 --> 00:33:00.850
Many times they were
alone, but sometimes older,

00:33:00.850 --> 00:33:03.600
hardened Iraqi men, who
looked at us with contempt

00:33:03.600 --> 00:33:05.530
and distrust joined them.

00:33:05.530 --> 00:33:07.920
I smiled and waved
at the children.

00:33:07.920 --> 00:33:10.440
They were ignorant of the
fact that I was doing so

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:12.750
with a semi-automatic
weapon positioned directly

00:33:12.750 --> 00:33:14.280
in front of me.

00:33:14.280 --> 00:33:16.050
When I saw the faces
of the adult men,

00:33:16.050 --> 00:33:18.185
I gripped my weapon just
a little bit tighter.

00:33:18.185 --> 00:33:19.560
I pressed the
button of my weapon

00:33:19.560 --> 00:33:23.010
deeper into my shoulder in
case any unforeseen events

00:33:23.010 --> 00:33:25.770
required me to have it
in position immediately.

00:33:25.770 --> 00:33:27.480
I would look each
man in his eyes

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:30.810
above the heads of the
small, simple children

00:33:30.810 --> 00:33:32.650
they were protecting.

00:33:32.650 --> 00:33:35.270
I matched the
contempt in their eyes

00:33:35.270 --> 00:33:36.992
with steely resolve in mine.

00:33:36.992 --> 00:33:38.450
They needed to know
that I wouldn't

00:33:38.450 --> 00:33:40.370
hesitate to pull
the trigger in case

00:33:40.370 --> 00:33:42.200
they wanted to try anything.

00:33:42.200 --> 00:33:44.480
I found myself locking
eyes with most of them

00:33:44.480 --> 00:33:47.080
until we were
safely out of view.

00:33:47.080 --> 00:33:48.700
I wondered what
they thought of us,

00:33:48.700 --> 00:33:51.010
American infidels who had
come to violently overthrow

00:33:51.010 --> 00:33:52.120
the regime.

00:33:52.120 --> 00:33:54.880
I saw a lot of children and
a lot of angry Iraqi men

00:33:54.880 --> 00:33:57.280
during those days on the convoy.

00:33:57.280 --> 00:33:59.110
I thought a lot about
how I would feel

00:33:59.110 --> 00:34:01.070
if the situation was reversed.

00:34:01.070 --> 00:34:03.250
What if my country had
been bombed into submission

00:34:03.250 --> 00:34:05.380
for reasons that
were still murky?

00:34:05.380 --> 00:34:08.050
What was it about America that
determined that we were always

00:34:08.050 --> 00:34:09.359
right in using force?

00:34:09.359 --> 00:34:10.900
If we were to listen
to what was told

00:34:10.900 --> 00:34:12.790
to us by the government
and our leaders,

00:34:12.790 --> 00:34:15.650
Saddam Hussein was a
bloodthirsty tyrant.

00:34:15.650 --> 00:34:19.480
He was to unleash weapons
of mass destruction

00:34:19.480 --> 00:34:22.510
onto an unsuspecting
American public.

00:34:22.510 --> 00:34:24.850
I just couldn't allow
myself to be convinced.

00:34:24.850 --> 00:34:28.510
Were the 9/11 attackers
not based in Afghanistan?

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:31.607
The shift from talking about
Afghanistan to focusing on Iraq

00:34:31.607 --> 00:34:33.190
was so swift and
smooth, I didn't even

00:34:33.190 --> 00:34:34.719
realize it happened.

00:34:34.719 --> 00:34:37.690
All I knew was that after
returning from the first six

00:34:37.690 --> 00:34:41.130
month deployment in Kuwait,
all talk had suddenly

00:34:41.130 --> 00:34:42.750
shifted to Iraq.

00:34:42.750 --> 00:34:45.229
I wanted to trust what
was being told to us,

00:34:45.229 --> 00:34:46.770
but the questions
in my head wouldn't

00:34:46.770 --> 00:34:48.960
allow me to do so fully.

00:34:48.960 --> 00:34:52.320
Was blind trust a prerequisite
to serving the country,

00:34:52.320 --> 00:34:54.270
or does it just make it
easier to do the job?

00:34:59.290 --> 00:35:01.790
JIMMY PEARSON: So I'll just ask
you one question about this,

00:35:01.790 --> 00:35:04.414
because I do want to open it up
for audience questions as well.

00:35:04.414 --> 00:35:05.390
ROB SMITH: Sure.

00:35:05.390 --> 00:35:06.260
JIMMY PEARSON: I
think what you see

00:35:06.260 --> 00:35:08.060
here is your point
that you made earlier

00:35:08.060 --> 00:35:09.895
about empathy kind of
made explicit, right?

00:35:09.895 --> 00:35:10.520
ROB SMITH: Yes.

00:35:10.520 --> 00:35:12.187
JIMMY PEARSON: As
you imagine what

00:35:12.187 --> 00:35:14.270
it's like to be those
children or those angry men.

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:17.570
And it's related to this
question of the doubt

00:35:17.570 --> 00:35:19.400
that you felt, and
whether that doubt was

00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:22.820
an impediment to you serving.

00:35:22.820 --> 00:35:24.860
So I guess that's
my question for you

00:35:24.860 --> 00:35:28.040
is, if you could say more
about whether you did feel that

00:35:28.040 --> 00:35:32.120
to some extent that empathy
was a blocker for you

00:35:32.120 --> 00:35:34.370
and something that made
this much more difficult.

00:35:34.370 --> 00:35:35.750
ROB SMITH: It was.

00:35:35.750 --> 00:35:43.830
Like I said in that
segment, or in that reading,

00:35:43.830 --> 00:35:45.450
there was a lot of
misinformation that

00:35:45.450 --> 00:35:47.190
was going on around that time.

00:35:47.190 --> 00:35:48.780
I mean, now we can
look back on it,

00:35:48.780 --> 00:35:53.500
and we can say we know
what it was about.

00:35:53.500 --> 00:35:55.170
And it wasn't necessarily
about the fear

00:35:55.170 --> 00:35:58.440
that Saddam Hussein had WMDs.

00:35:58.440 --> 00:36:01.890
And there was a lot of
doubt, a lot of fear,

00:36:01.890 --> 00:36:04.920
a lot of conversations going on
between me and other soldiers.

00:36:04.920 --> 00:36:07.120
And I get into that a
little bit in the book.

00:36:07.120 --> 00:36:10.200
There's a lot of talk about
exactly why are we here.

00:36:10.200 --> 00:36:12.957
There's a lot of rumors about
Saddam's going to be over,

00:36:12.957 --> 00:36:14.790
and they're going to
love us, and we're just

00:36:14.790 --> 00:36:16.706
going to be out of here
in a couple of months.

00:36:16.706 --> 00:36:17.695
And that didn't happen.

00:36:17.695 --> 00:36:18.570
JIMMY PEARSON: Right.

00:36:18.570 --> 00:36:20.770
ROB SMITH: It's quite
obvious that didn't happen.

00:36:20.770 --> 00:36:26.070
But I do think that being
an other in the military,

00:36:26.070 --> 00:36:28.410
being a black person
in the military--

00:36:28.410 --> 00:36:31.350
and I deal with some of the
racial issues more explicitly

00:36:31.350 --> 00:36:33.184
earlier on when I talk
about basic training.

00:36:33.184 --> 00:36:35.266
Because when I was in basic
training in the south,

00:36:35.266 --> 00:36:37.590
I was the only black person
in the entire company.

00:36:37.590 --> 00:36:39.669
But I think that
when you're there,

00:36:39.669 --> 00:36:42.210
and you're dealing with a lot
of-- let me tell you something,

00:36:42.210 --> 00:36:44.130
you're dealing with a
lot of good old boys.

00:36:44.130 --> 00:36:46.170
And you're dealing, in
a lot of situations,

00:36:46.170 --> 00:36:49.380
where sometimes you are one of
the only black people around.

00:36:49.380 --> 00:36:53.400
And you will kind of
understand and get

00:36:53.400 --> 00:36:57.450
a kind of an inside view
of how people treat others.

00:36:57.450 --> 00:36:59.190
I talk a little bit
about in the book

00:36:59.190 --> 00:37:02.230
about how they used to call
the Iraq people like haji.

00:37:02.230 --> 00:37:04.460
You know, haji but better
not mess up, or haji better

00:37:04.460 --> 00:37:06.418
not do this, because
we'll put a bullet in him,

00:37:06.418 --> 00:37:07.560
all that other stuff.

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:12.700
And just as a black person,
as a black man, I just--

00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:16.030
some of the conversations
and some of the behaviors

00:37:16.030 --> 00:37:18.430
just felt to me
intrinsically wrong.

00:37:18.430 --> 00:37:19.850
And I get into
that a little bit.

00:37:19.850 --> 00:37:24.430
But I do feel like I had more
empathy going in that situation

00:37:24.430 --> 00:37:27.210
just as a person of color.

00:37:27.210 --> 00:37:29.380
And I will identify
myself as a person

00:37:29.380 --> 00:37:31.940
of color in that instance.

00:37:31.940 --> 00:37:33.940
Because that's something
that I shared in common

00:37:33.940 --> 00:37:35.560
with them, the Iraqi people.

00:37:35.560 --> 00:37:37.370
Like we are both
people of color.

00:37:37.370 --> 00:37:39.170
And when you look
at the military,

00:37:39.170 --> 00:37:43.540
it was these overwhelmingly
white male forces

00:37:43.540 --> 00:37:47.060
that were coming in to kind
of dominate that situation.

00:37:47.060 --> 00:37:51.130
So I think that it did help me
look at it through a lens that

00:37:51.130 --> 00:37:53.470
was a lot different,
which brings it

00:37:53.470 --> 00:37:56.170
back to why I thought it was
so important to put this out.

00:37:56.170 --> 00:37:58.630
Because the lens of--

00:37:58.630 --> 00:38:00.160
taking the gay out of it--

00:38:00.160 --> 00:38:03.070
the lens of the military,
a view of the military

00:38:03.070 --> 00:38:05.470
through the lens of
a black man, is not

00:38:05.470 --> 00:38:08.410
something that exists enough.

00:38:08.410 --> 00:38:10.390
JIMMY PEARSON: Yeah.

00:38:10.390 --> 00:38:12.470
All right, I have a ton
of follow-up questions,

00:38:12.470 --> 00:38:14.220
and stuff about my own
personal experience

00:38:14.220 --> 00:38:16.130
that we'll talk
about afterwards.

00:38:16.130 --> 00:38:18.160
But I do want to make
sure that everyone

00:38:18.160 --> 00:38:20.470
has time to ask questions,
and we're at a quarter till.

00:38:20.470 --> 00:38:23.150
So reminder, if you
do have questions,

00:38:23.150 --> 00:38:27.260
please line up behind the
mics, and we'll open it up.

00:38:29.807 --> 00:38:31.390
I think you're the
only one right now.

00:38:31.390 --> 00:38:32.375
AUDIENCE: Right to the front?

00:38:32.375 --> 00:38:32.840
ROB SMITH: Yes.

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:34.340
I'm so glad somebody
had a question,

00:38:34.340 --> 00:38:36.980
because it's so awkward
when people don't.

00:38:36.980 --> 00:38:38.780
It's the worst.

00:38:38.780 --> 00:38:42.960
AUDIENCE: So my question
comes out of the first reading

00:38:42.960 --> 00:38:45.800
that you had from your book,
when you talked about coming

00:38:45.800 --> 00:38:47.480
out to your mother.

00:38:47.480 --> 00:38:50.900
And you mentioned
to her quoting how

00:38:50.900 --> 00:38:52.900
it wasn't part of God's plan.

00:38:52.900 --> 00:38:54.900
And I often hear about
people using religion

00:38:54.900 --> 00:38:58.280
as a stick to beat back what's
uncomfortable or strange

00:38:58.280 --> 00:38:59.390
to them.

00:38:59.390 --> 00:39:01.280
And I'm wondering,
it sounds like you

00:39:01.280 --> 00:39:05.810
come from a household that
had a good deal of faith,

00:39:05.810 --> 00:39:08.480
or at least, that was
part of the culture.

00:39:08.480 --> 00:39:11.210
And I was wondering if you could
talk about your experiences

00:39:11.210 --> 00:39:15.660
coming out to those with
kind of a faith upbringing

00:39:15.660 --> 00:39:17.180
and in that community.

00:39:17.180 --> 00:39:21.200
And then, on top of
that, if you, yourself,

00:39:21.200 --> 00:39:25.490
have found a faith group that
is accepting to you since.

00:39:25.490 --> 00:39:28.220
ROB SMITH: Yeah,
that's interesting.

00:39:28.220 --> 00:39:32.120
I did I grew up in a Christian
household, African Methodist

00:39:32.120 --> 00:39:35.100
Episcopal to be specific.

00:39:35.100 --> 00:39:41.120
And I know a lot of people,
particularly black gay men,

00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:43.690
who were born and
raised in the church,

00:39:43.690 --> 00:39:47.870
and who were born and raised
in homophobic churches.

00:39:47.870 --> 00:39:52.220
And when you internalize
those messages

00:39:52.220 --> 00:39:55.520
when you're very young, they can
be very, very hard to overcome.

00:39:55.520 --> 00:39:57.980
And I've spoken to people
that have had that experience

00:39:57.980 --> 00:39:59.120
in their churches.

00:39:59.120 --> 00:40:02.140
For me, I didn't
have that experience

00:40:02.140 --> 00:40:03.650
in my church growing up.

00:40:03.650 --> 00:40:06.020
I never heard
anything either way

00:40:06.020 --> 00:40:09.650
about anything gay in my church.

00:40:09.650 --> 00:40:11.970
It was just never about that.

00:40:11.970 --> 00:40:17.090
And so I feel like I'm able to
have a relationship with God

00:40:17.090 --> 00:40:20.600
right now, but it doesn't
have that baggage on it, where

00:40:20.600 --> 00:40:23.429
I had to come back and realize
that oh, all of these things

00:40:23.429 --> 00:40:25.220
that were being told
to me about being gay,

00:40:25.220 --> 00:40:27.080
or homosexuality, or
whatever were wrong,

00:40:27.080 --> 00:40:30.560
and they were a perversion
of what the Bible is saying

00:40:30.560 --> 00:40:33.220
and all that stuff.

00:40:33.220 --> 00:40:36.250
To be more specific about a
faith community that I found,

00:40:36.250 --> 00:40:40.150
I'm more spiritual than overtly
religious at this point.

00:40:40.150 --> 00:40:42.910
There were-- I
mean, at my wedding,

00:40:42.910 --> 00:40:46.990
I have a friend that's a choir
master at a church on the Upper

00:40:46.990 --> 00:40:47.920
East Side.

00:40:47.920 --> 00:40:51.460
He semi-officiated my ceremony.

00:40:51.460 --> 00:40:52.540
We jumped the broom.

00:40:52.540 --> 00:40:55.554
And everybody who's-- everybody
knows the slave tradition

00:40:55.554 --> 00:40:57.220
of jumping the broom
and all that stuff.

00:40:57.220 --> 00:40:58.600
They jumped the
broom because they

00:40:58.600 --> 00:40:59.808
weren't unable to be married.

00:40:59.808 --> 00:41:01.180
And so I did that at my wedding.

00:41:01.180 --> 00:41:04.090
And I have a kind
of mentor that is

00:41:04.090 --> 00:41:08.650
a black gay pastor at an
affirming church on the Upper

00:41:08.650 --> 00:41:09.610
West Side.

00:41:09.610 --> 00:41:15.010
So that's what my relationship
is to faith and Christianity

00:41:15.010 --> 00:41:15.730
right now.

00:41:15.730 --> 00:41:18.740
And I know that some people
in the community hate it.

00:41:18.740 --> 00:41:21.700
They hate anything that
has to do with faith,

00:41:21.700 --> 00:41:25.600
because there are so many
people who use faith, and who

00:41:25.600 --> 00:41:27.804
use Christianity, and
who use these things,

00:41:27.804 --> 00:41:29.470
and they pervert those
messages in order

00:41:29.470 --> 00:41:31.900
to ostracize people
that are gay,

00:41:31.900 --> 00:41:33.950
and people in the
LGBTQ community.

00:41:33.950 --> 00:41:38.410
And I understand why people
are so hesitant to embrace it.

00:41:38.410 --> 00:41:40.810
I've never really
had that experience.

00:41:40.810 --> 00:41:42.845
And my mother brought that up.

00:41:42.845 --> 00:41:44.720
And by the way, we're
on very good terms now.

00:41:44.720 --> 00:41:47.140
These things
happened a while ago.

00:41:47.140 --> 00:41:49.030
So we were able to kind
of come back around.

00:41:49.030 --> 00:41:51.070
And I say, look,
parents are people too.

00:41:51.070 --> 00:41:53.260
And coming out isn't always
an after-school special.

00:41:53.260 --> 00:41:56.470
Mine certainly wasn't.

00:41:56.470 --> 00:41:58.510
But she was going through
a lot at the time.

00:41:58.510 --> 00:42:01.150
She got cancer twice.

00:42:01.150 --> 00:42:04.480
And she was at a
point in her life

00:42:04.480 --> 00:42:06.520
where she was very
religious, and that's

00:42:06.520 --> 00:42:08.770
where that was coming from.

00:42:08.770 --> 00:42:11.320
So I would say that my
relationship with Christianity

00:42:11.320 --> 00:42:14.040
right now is fairly strong.

00:42:14.040 --> 00:42:15.790
JIMMY PEARSON: Thank
you for the question.

00:42:15.790 --> 00:42:18.480
ROB SMITH: Sure.

00:42:18.480 --> 00:42:19.462
Who was first?

00:42:19.462 --> 00:42:20.420
AUDIENCE: I don't know.

00:42:20.420 --> 00:42:20.700
ROB SMITH: OK.

00:42:20.700 --> 00:42:21.450
JIMMY PEARSON: Why
don't you go ahead.

00:42:21.450 --> 00:42:22.722
We'll split mic to mic.

00:42:22.722 --> 00:42:24.555
AUDIENCE: Thank you so
much for coming here,

00:42:24.555 --> 00:42:26.221
and I really appreciate
you speaking out

00:42:26.221 --> 00:42:27.680
about your experiences.

00:42:27.680 --> 00:42:29.720
My question is about the
people you served with.

00:42:29.720 --> 00:42:31.178
Do you have an
ongoing relationship

00:42:31.178 --> 00:42:32.827
with a lot of the
people that you

00:42:32.827 --> 00:42:34.202
served with when
you weren't out,

00:42:34.202 --> 00:42:36.810
and did you have to come out
to them, and how did that go?

00:42:36.810 --> 00:42:40.350
ROB SMITH: Yeah, well I will
say Facebook is a powerful tool.

00:42:40.350 --> 00:42:41.970
That might get edited out.

00:42:41.970 --> 00:42:44.580
No, Facebook is a
really powerful tool

00:42:44.580 --> 00:42:45.810
to just connect with people.

00:42:45.810 --> 00:42:48.300
And I'm friends with,
I'm Facebook friends

00:42:48.300 --> 00:42:49.680
with people that I served.

00:42:49.680 --> 00:42:51.360
And we're in open dialogue.

00:42:51.360 --> 00:42:53.610
As a matter of fact, somebody
just commented on a post

00:42:53.610 --> 00:42:55.567
that I made about
this the other day.

00:42:55.567 --> 00:42:57.150
And he asked me if
he was in the book.

00:42:57.150 --> 00:42:58.230
And I said, yeah,
you're right there.

00:42:58.230 --> 00:43:00.563
Of course, your name has been
changed, because I changed

00:43:00.563 --> 00:43:03.810
everybody else's name but mine.

00:43:03.810 --> 00:43:06.870
So I do still have those
relationships with them.

00:43:06.870 --> 00:43:09.150
And the reactions
when I came out,

00:43:09.150 --> 00:43:12.752
and I got into a lot of heavy
activist work when Don't Ask,

00:43:12.752 --> 00:43:14.460
Don't Tell was still
the law of the land.

00:43:14.460 --> 00:43:16.751
I was arrested at the White
House protesting Don't Ask,

00:43:16.751 --> 00:43:17.850
Don't Tell.

00:43:17.850 --> 00:43:20.502
And then when a lot of
that stuff was happening,

00:43:20.502 --> 00:43:22.960
they would kind of hit me up
via social media and all that.

00:43:22.960 --> 00:43:25.750
And it ranged from we kind
of figured you were gay,

00:43:25.750 --> 00:43:27.450
but nobody really cared to--

00:43:27.450 --> 00:43:28.720
oh, this is a big surprise.

00:43:28.720 --> 00:43:30.630
But you know what, it doesn't
make a difference to me,

00:43:30.630 --> 00:43:32.330
because, you know,
you were still Smitty,

00:43:32.330 --> 00:43:34.121
you know, you're still
Smitty, you're still

00:43:34.121 --> 00:43:36.580
a soldier, stuff like that.

00:43:36.580 --> 00:43:42.210
So I do have those
relationships still to this day.

00:43:42.210 --> 00:43:44.040
And I guess the
worst part about it

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:45.980
is that I know that
those relationships could

00:43:45.980 --> 00:43:47.380
have been stronger.

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:51.616
But it was just, with that law,
it just wasn't good timing.

00:43:51.616 --> 00:43:52.470
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:52.470 --> 00:43:53.350
ROB SMITH: Sure.

00:43:53.350 --> 00:43:54.775
And you had one?

00:43:54.775 --> 00:43:55.650
AUDIENCE: Yes, hello.

00:43:55.650 --> 00:43:56.520
ROB SMITH: Hi.

00:43:56.520 --> 00:43:58.103
AUDIENCE: Hi, my
name is Kelsy, I just

00:43:58.103 --> 00:44:00.564
wanted to thank you so
much for being here,

00:44:00.564 --> 00:44:02.984
and for serving our country,
and for sharing your story.

00:44:02.984 --> 00:44:04.596
You kind of stole
my question, so I'm

00:44:04.596 --> 00:44:06.750
going to tweak mine a
little bit, if that's OK.

00:44:06.750 --> 00:44:09.594
So you spoke about how it was
really hard for you to come out

00:44:09.594 --> 00:44:11.840
to you mom, and you
couldn't, obviously, come out

00:44:11.840 --> 00:44:13.185
when you were in the military.

00:44:13.185 --> 00:44:15.660
So who did you confide
in during that time,

00:44:15.660 --> 00:44:18.774
and how did you cope with the
mental health aspect of it?

00:44:18.774 --> 00:44:21.570
Because I know, when
you're hiding who you are,

00:44:21.570 --> 00:44:23.610
sometimes it brings
depression or anxiety.

00:44:23.610 --> 00:44:27.127
So how did you cope with that
and who did you confide in?

00:44:27.127 --> 00:44:29.210
ROB SMITH: You know, right
after the first reading

00:44:29.210 --> 00:44:33.650
I did, I talk about the night
that I almost ended my life.

00:44:33.650 --> 00:44:38.330
And I talked to my sister, who
was and remains my best friend,

00:44:38.330 --> 00:44:40.130
and she kind of talked
me off the ledge.

00:44:40.130 --> 00:44:44.120
So when I was in the military,
I confided with her a lot.

00:44:44.120 --> 00:44:47.270
There are people that I
came out to on the sly

00:44:47.270 --> 00:44:49.250
when I was in the military.

00:44:49.250 --> 00:44:51.900
But to tell you the truth,
at that point in my life,

00:44:51.900 --> 00:44:54.560
it was a very kind
of lonely road.

00:44:54.560 --> 00:44:57.440
And I'm really glad that she
brought up the conversation

00:44:57.440 --> 00:44:58.820
about mental health.

00:44:58.820 --> 00:45:00.620
I speak out about
an organization

00:45:00.620 --> 00:45:01.890
called the Soldiers Project.

00:45:01.890 --> 00:45:04.100
If nobody knows what
the Soldiers Project is,

00:45:04.100 --> 00:45:07.220
it is an organization-- you
go to soldiersproject.org,

00:45:07.220 --> 00:45:09.920
and if you are a veteran,
or even active duty,

00:45:09.920 --> 00:45:11.600
I believe, in the
armed forces, they

00:45:11.600 --> 00:45:15.020
have a network of
therapists and psychiatrists

00:45:15.020 --> 00:45:16.310
that work for free.

00:45:16.310 --> 00:45:19.430
And they will connect you
to somebody in your area

00:45:19.430 --> 00:45:21.840
within 24 to 48 hours.

00:45:21.840 --> 00:45:24.230
I didn't really
start taking control

00:45:24.230 --> 00:45:27.320
of my mental health
and dealing with what

00:45:27.320 --> 00:45:29.790
I needed to do in that realm
until about maybe five,

00:45:29.790 --> 00:45:31.700
six years ago.

00:45:31.700 --> 00:45:34.970
And I found my therapist
through the Soldiers Project.

00:45:34.970 --> 00:45:37.959
And it has been an
immense help for me

00:45:37.959 --> 00:45:40.250
to work through some of the
stuff that is in this book.

00:45:40.250 --> 00:45:42.680
And also, some of
the mental health

00:45:42.680 --> 00:45:47.150
stuff that just comes with being
a gay person in this society.

00:45:47.150 --> 00:45:51.480
You are just not like
87% of other people.

00:45:51.480 --> 00:45:54.890
And I think that
we kid ourselves

00:45:54.890 --> 00:46:01.560
when we ignore the mental stress
that comes along with that.

00:46:01.560 --> 00:46:04.920
So that was the way--
to answer your question,

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:07.700
I wasn't able to start taking
care of my mental health

00:46:07.700 --> 00:46:09.800
until about six or
seven years ago.

00:46:09.800 --> 00:46:12.860
Because it was
really time to start

00:46:12.860 --> 00:46:16.077
dealing with some of the issues
that this work brings up.

00:46:16.077 --> 00:46:16.910
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:46:16.910 --> 00:46:17.972
ROB SMITH: Thank you.

00:46:17.972 --> 00:46:19.430
Thanks for giving
me an opportunity

00:46:19.430 --> 00:46:20.900
to mention the Soldiers Project.

00:46:20.900 --> 00:46:22.354
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:22.354 --> 00:46:23.520
ROB SMITH: Yeah, absolutely.

00:46:23.520 --> 00:46:24.970
JIMMY PEARSON: Yeah, definitely.

00:46:24.970 --> 00:46:27.640
ROB SMITH: They give me nothing
but free mental health care,

00:46:27.640 --> 00:46:28.139
by the way.

00:46:30.169 --> 00:46:31.794
AUDIENCE: Thank you
so much for coming.

00:46:31.794 --> 00:46:32.750
Fascinating story.

00:46:32.750 --> 00:46:34.840
And thank you for your service.

00:46:34.840 --> 00:46:36.390
One of the things--

00:46:36.390 --> 00:46:42.180
you're intersecting in so many
interesting ways, soldier,

00:46:42.180 --> 00:46:43.990
veteran, gay, black.

00:46:43.990 --> 00:46:53.340
And I know in my experience
as a gay white man,

00:46:53.340 --> 00:46:55.228
I don't have to--

00:46:55.228 --> 00:46:57.470
well, another aspect
of my identity

00:46:57.470 --> 00:47:01.660
is that I'm a Christian, which
I don't reveal much here.

00:47:01.660 --> 00:47:02.710
ROB SMITH: OK.

00:47:02.710 --> 00:47:04.710
AUDIENCE: So I'm wondering
are the other aspects

00:47:04.710 --> 00:47:07.120
of your identity that you
found easier to expose.

00:47:07.120 --> 00:47:09.990
Like in your workplace, is
it easier to be a veteran

00:47:09.990 --> 00:47:13.030
or easier to be gay?

00:47:13.030 --> 00:47:17.620
ROB SMITH: I'll
tell you, you want

00:47:17.620 --> 00:47:19.990
you to be completely
honest, in any workplace,

00:47:19.990 --> 00:47:21.640
it's not easy to
be anything that's

00:47:21.640 --> 00:47:24.490
not heterosexual and white.

00:47:24.490 --> 00:47:27.941
Let's just keep it
all the way real.

00:47:27.941 --> 00:47:30.440
When I think about identities
and which one is easier to be,

00:47:30.440 --> 00:47:32.665
I mean, I would
think that for me--

00:47:35.850 --> 00:47:37.920
that's a tough one,
because to me, it's

00:47:37.920 --> 00:47:39.360
not about what's
easier, it's not

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:41.490
about what identity is
easier to be for me,

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:45.370
it's about fully inhabiting
all of my identities.

00:47:45.370 --> 00:47:47.040
And I feel like
I've done the work

00:47:47.040 --> 00:47:49.980
to get to this point, where
I'm comfortable enough

00:47:49.980 --> 00:47:53.910
with who I am that what other
people think of me, based

00:47:53.910 --> 00:47:57.762
on these things, don't matter.

00:47:57.762 --> 00:48:01.750
[APPLAUSE]

00:48:01.750 --> 00:48:06.980
So I can't take on--
oh, my god, you know,

00:48:06.980 --> 00:48:09.050
is everybody going
to think that I'm

00:48:09.050 --> 00:48:10.730
less capable because I'm black.

00:48:10.730 --> 00:48:12.920
Or are they going to
think that I shouldn't

00:48:12.920 --> 00:48:14.660
be on camera because I'm gay.

00:48:14.660 --> 00:48:17.490
Or are they going to think I'm
crazy, because I'm a veteran.

00:48:17.490 --> 00:48:20.810
You know, I physically
can't take those things on.

00:48:20.810 --> 00:48:24.050
So I have to own all of
these identities in any space

00:48:24.050 --> 00:48:25.850
that I enter into.

00:48:25.850 --> 00:48:30.020
And this is-- I mean, look, I'm
dealing in finance right now,

00:48:30.020 --> 00:48:31.720
where I am dealing with--

00:48:31.720 --> 00:48:34.490
the majority of people
that I deal with

00:48:34.490 --> 00:48:36.290
are white and straight.

00:48:36.290 --> 00:48:40.310
And if I kind of
carry that baggage

00:48:40.310 --> 00:48:42.290
from my identities
on my back, it

00:48:42.290 --> 00:48:46.430
would really hinder my
ability to do my job

00:48:46.430 --> 00:48:47.960
and to be effective in my job.

00:48:47.960 --> 00:48:49.910
I hope that answers
the question.

00:48:49.910 --> 00:48:52.750
So to completely
answer the question,

00:48:52.750 --> 00:48:55.640
there is no one thing
that's easier than the other

00:48:55.640 --> 00:48:56.600
to deal with.

00:48:56.600 --> 00:48:59.750
I will tell you that as a
black man in society, that is

00:48:59.750 --> 00:49:01.280
the identity that people see.

00:49:01.280 --> 00:49:03.710
That is how I am treated.

00:49:03.710 --> 00:49:06.560
People don't know gay, and
they don't know veteran,

00:49:06.560 --> 00:49:08.150
but they know black.

00:49:08.150 --> 00:49:11.210
And that is how I'm
treated more so.

00:49:11.210 --> 00:49:14.060
So that is that kind
of discrimination

00:49:14.060 --> 00:49:17.510
that is more overt to me
in my life than anything

00:49:17.510 --> 00:49:22.571
based on religion or sexuality.

00:49:22.571 --> 00:49:23.525
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:49:23.525 --> 00:49:24.960
JIMMY PEARSON: Hey.

00:49:24.960 --> 00:49:27.870
AUDIENCE: So you talked a
bit about misconceptions

00:49:27.870 --> 00:49:29.490
in the broader
population about what

00:49:29.490 --> 00:49:34.050
it means to be in the military,
or just lack of knowledge.

00:49:34.050 --> 00:49:39.000
And I was wondering what
you thought or believed

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:42.870
about the military before
you decided to enlist

00:49:42.870 --> 00:49:46.770
and where those ideas came from.

00:49:46.770 --> 00:49:50.720
ROB SMITH: I was
very young, I was 17.

00:49:50.720 --> 00:49:52.740
Yeah, obviously,
five years ago-- no.

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:56.910
So I was I 17, I was very young.

00:49:56.910 --> 00:49:59.710
And my ideas about
the military were--

00:49:59.710 --> 00:50:02.364
so, one of the things that--
this is a story that you're not

00:50:02.364 --> 00:50:03.780
going to get from
a straight book,

00:50:03.780 --> 00:50:05.370
is about how I was
completely obsessed

00:50:05.370 --> 00:50:07.080
with my military recruiter.

00:50:07.080 --> 00:50:09.220
He was just gorgeous.

00:50:09.220 --> 00:50:10.170
Oh, my god.

00:50:10.170 --> 00:50:10.840
I mean he--

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:12.756
JIMMY PEARSON: They pick
them for that reason.

00:50:12.756 --> 00:50:14.650
ROB SMITH: They do, I
mean, they really do.

00:50:14.650 --> 00:50:17.850
And this is-- there's some
embarrassing stuff in there

00:50:17.850 --> 00:50:21.210
about how my heart just went
pitter-patter when he came by.

00:50:21.210 --> 00:50:23.910
But he was filling
my head with a lot

00:50:23.910 --> 00:50:26.259
of stories about how
it'd be just like camping

00:50:26.259 --> 00:50:27.300
and all that other stuff.

00:50:27.300 --> 00:50:29.258
So I was getting this
idea, well, the infantry,

00:50:29.258 --> 00:50:30.604
that will be cool.

00:50:30.604 --> 00:50:33.020
And you know, I'll get to sleep
out, and I'll get to camp,

00:50:33.020 --> 00:50:34.436
and I'll get to
do all this stuff.

00:50:34.436 --> 00:50:35.790
Mind you, 17 years old.

00:50:35.790 --> 00:50:37.830
That was not the case.

00:50:37.830 --> 00:50:43.330
So those ideas of the military
did not come to fruition.

00:50:43.330 --> 00:50:45.340
It was definitely
not summer camp.

00:50:45.340 --> 00:50:49.600
It was no fairy tale
or anything like that.

00:50:49.600 --> 00:50:56.270
But like I said before, I think
that the experiences that I've

00:50:56.270 --> 00:50:58.400
had just made me stronger.

00:50:58.400 --> 00:51:00.590
It made me kind of unbreakable.

00:51:00.590 --> 00:51:02.570
And I wouldn't wish
some of the stuff

00:51:02.570 --> 00:51:04.790
that I went through on anybody.

00:51:04.790 --> 00:51:08.180
But I do believe that right now,
when we have things like-- when

00:51:08.180 --> 00:51:13.250
Don't Ask, Don't Tell is over,
and the military is trying

00:51:13.250 --> 00:51:16.730
to come, I guess, into 2017.

00:51:16.730 --> 00:51:18.230
Slowly, but surely,
they'll be here,

00:51:18.230 --> 00:51:20.480
even though there's still
some issues with transgender

00:51:20.480 --> 00:51:23.270
soldiers that we're still
trying to work out nowadays.

00:51:23.270 --> 00:51:26.190
And nobody knows what's
going on with that.

00:51:26.190 --> 00:51:32.090
But I do think that there are
a lot of positive qualities

00:51:32.090 --> 00:51:33.062
that the military has.

00:51:33.062 --> 00:51:34.520
There's a lot of
positive qualities

00:51:34.520 --> 00:51:36.950
that it can instill
in a lot of people.

00:51:36.950 --> 00:51:38.840
And I'd never want
to bash the military.

00:51:38.840 --> 00:51:42.267
I only bash discrimination,
discriminatory policies,

00:51:42.267 --> 00:51:43.350
and discriminatory people.

00:51:46.052 --> 00:51:48.510
AUDIENCE: I feel really bad,
because I know you're waiting,

00:51:48.510 --> 00:51:50.968
but I think that has to be our
last question, because we're

00:51:50.968 --> 00:51:52.780
about out of time.

00:51:52.780 --> 00:51:53.720
I really am sorry.

00:51:53.720 --> 00:51:54.950
But Rob is going to hang
out for a while afterwards.

00:51:54.950 --> 00:51:55.949
ROB SMITH: I'll be here.

00:51:55.949 --> 00:51:57.344
I'll hang out, so we'll talk.

00:51:57.344 --> 00:51:59.760
JIMMY PEARSON: And I did want
to have one last opportunity

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:01.380
to say thank you to Rob.

00:52:01.380 --> 00:52:04.670
A, for joining us, but B, on a
personal note, as a sailor who

00:52:04.670 --> 00:52:08.120
served both before and after
Don't Ask, Don't Tell repeal,

00:52:08.120 --> 00:52:10.635
for your activism, and helping
to get that policy repealed,

00:52:10.635 --> 00:52:11.260
and everything.

00:52:11.260 --> 00:52:11.640
ROB SMITH: Absolutely.

00:52:11.640 --> 00:52:12.650
Thank you for your service.

00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:13.691
JIMMY PEARSON: Thank you.

00:52:13.691 --> 00:52:14.859
Thank you for your service.

00:52:14.859 --> 00:52:16.400
Thank you again to
Rob, and thank you

00:52:16.400 --> 00:52:19.890
to everyone for coming
and for your questions.

